column42: ETHYLENE OXIDE OR ETHYLENE OXIDE WITH NITROGEN UP TO A TOTAL PRESSURE OF 1MPA (10 BAR) AT 50 DEGREES C
column168: WHILE MAKING A DELIVERY PRIOR TO THE SALEM HOSPITAL, THE DRIVER TOOK THE TWO CARTONS OF ETHYLENE OXIDE OFF HIS TRAILER SO THEY WOULD NOT BE DAMAGED WHILE MAKING THIS DELIVERY.  SINCE THIS DELIVERY WAS A GROUND DROP, HE PLACED THE TWO CARTONS ON THE ICC BUMPER OF THE TRAILER.  WHEN THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETE, HE FORGOT ABOUT THE TWO CARTONS AND NEVER PUT THEM BACK INTO HIS TRAILER.  HE THEN PULLED OUT OF THIS DELIVERY AND CONTINUED ON HIS ROUTE.  WHEN HE ARRIVED AT HIS NEXT DELIVERY, A FEW BLOCKS AWAY, HE REMEMBERED ABOUT THE CARTONS.  HE THEN BACKTRACKED HIS ROUTE TO LOCATE THEM.  UPON ARRIVING BACK AT THE PRIOR DELIVERY, THEY HAD ONE CARTON WHICH THEY FOUND SITTING IN THEIR YARD.  THE 2ND CARTONS WAS NOT LOCATED.  AT THE SAME TIME, THE SECOND BOX WAS FOUND ON THE STREET BY A PASSER BY.  IT IS TAKEN TO SALEM FIRE DEPARTMENT.  DEPUTY MONROE PULLED THE PACKING LIST AND CONTACTED THE SHIPPER 3M, WHO THEN CALLED US.  DEPUTY MONROE ADVISED THAT THE CARTON SHOWED SIGNS OF BEING HIT, BUT DID NOT APPEAR TO BE LEAKING.  WE THEN HAD THE DRIVER GO TO THE FIRE DEPARTMENT TO PICK UP THE CARTON AND TAKE IT TO THE HOSPITAL.  WHEN THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE HOSPITAL, THEY CHECKED THE CARTON WITH A METER AND REFUSE IT AS POSSIBLY LEAKING.  WITH THE POSSIBILITY OF A LEAKING CARTON, WE HAD TRIED TO CONTACT A CLEAN UP COMPANY BUT WERE UNABLE TO SECURE ONE.  SINCE THE HOSPITAL RECEIVING WAS CLOSING AT THIS TIME WE SEND AN OVERPACK TO THE HOSPITAL AND HAD THE CARTON PLACED INSIDE.  THE OVERPACK WAS THEN RETURNED TO OUR TERMINAL AND HELD UNTIL A HAZ-MAT COMPANY COULD BE GOT TO INSPECT THE CARTON.  HMHTTC WAS CALLED FOR THIS.  UPON THERE INSPECT AND MIGRATION THEY FOUND THAT 1 OF 12 CYLINDERS HAD LEAKED AND WAS EMPTY.  THE CONTENTS WERE REPACKED FOR SHIPPING BY HMHTTC AND RETURN TO THE SHIPPER.
column169: WHILE THE INCIDENT WAS BEING INVESTIGATED, THE DRIVER UNDERSTOOD HIS ERROR AND THE POSSIBLE HARM THAT COULD HAVE COME TO IT.  HE WAS RE-INSTRUCTED IN THE PROPER HANDLING OF HAZARDS MATERIAL.

column168: WHILE A TRUCK WAS BEING LOADED TO GO TO FORT AMANDA 44% HCHO..IT OVERFLOWED INTO THE LOAD RACK SUMP.. MATERIAL WAS ON THE GROUND 40 MINUTES.  AFFECTED AREA WAS APPROX 10' X 20'  HOW WAS THE INCIDENT DISCOVERED?  TRUCK DRIVER SHUT OFF THE EMERGENCY STOP BUTTON.. THEN CAME INTO THE CONTROL ROOM AND INFORMED ME THAT HCHO WAS RUNNING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TRUCK.   WHAT WERE THE CONTRIBUTING FACTORS TO THIS INCIDENT?  OPERATOR WAS WATCHING GAUGE IN THE BUILDING AND THOUGHT IT WAS LESS THAN WHAT IT ACTUALLY WAS (MISREAD GAUGE).. HE WAS IN A  DAZE AND THINKING AHEAD TO THE NEXT TRUCK IN LINE WAITING..{DAY DREAMING} HE WAS BUSY AND LOST TRACK OF GAUGE.  WHAT INTERIM ACTIONS WERE TAKEN?  THE EMERGENCY STOP WAS SHUT OFF WHEN OVER FLOW WAS DETECTED.. AND THE TOP OF THE TRUCK WAS WASHED DOWN AS WELL AS THE GROUND UNDER THE LOAD RACK.. THE MATERIAL WAS RECOVERED TO T91 DILUTE TANK. WHAT SUGGESTIONS DO YOU HAVE TO PREVENT THIS INCIDENT FROM REOCCURING?  PAY MORE ATTENTION TO JOB AT HAND.. AND TO PLACE PUMP SHUT OFFS ON METER SO THIS WOULDN'T HAPPEN AGAIN...

column168: AT 10:00 AM A DRIVER CALLED IN TO REPORT A DAMAGED PKG CONTAINING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS, INDICATED BY A DIAMOND CORROSIVE LABEL.  THE DRIVER WAS INSTRUCTED NOT TO TOUCH THE PKG AND TO SECURE THE VEHICLE UNTIL A RESPONDER ARRIVED TO EXTRACT THE CORROSIVE SUBSTANCE.  WHILE WEARING REQUIRED PPE, THE RESPONDER FOLLOWED THE DECISION TREE AND APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET (CORROSIVE), AND REMOVED THE SPILL SAFELY.  THE BOX WAS LOADED ON THE FLOOR BLOCKED AND BRACED ON THE REAR PASSENGER SIDE CORNER.  NO LIQUID WAS RELEASED INTO THE CAR, ALL CONTAINED WITHIN THE PACKAGE.  AFTER FURTHER INVESTIGATION, A COMBINATION BROKEN SEAL, LOOSE CAP ATTRIBUTED TO INTERNAL CORROSION CAUSING BOX INTEGRITY TO FAIL.  THE CARTON AND CORROSIVE SUBSTANCE WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMP PROCEDURES AND THE NON-CONTAMINATED BOTTLES REPACKAGED & RETURNED TO SHIPPER VIA SALVAGE DRUM.

AN IMTT SUPERVISOR CLEANED THE TANK RAIL CAR SECURED THE PLUG ON THE VALVE.  THE RAIL CAR HAD APPROXIMATELY 600 GALLONS OF BUTANOL IN IT. column168: TANK CAR, UTLX 46821, LOAD ETHYL ACETATE, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING AT CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN AVON, IN.  PRODUCT WAS LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF CAR CONTINUOUSLY WHILE IT WAS SITTING STILL AND WAS DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOALTED AND SORBENT PADS WERE PLACED UNDER THE CAR TO CONTAIN THE LEAKAGE.  CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO REPAIR THE LEAK AND TO CONDUCT ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP.  THE SHIPPER, BP AMOCO CHEMICAL, WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CONTRACTOR REPORTED THAT THE CAR WAS NOT LEAKING WHEN THEY ARRIVED.  THEY FOUND THAT THE 2 INCH LIQUID VALVE WAS BEARLY THREADED ONTO THE LIQUID EDUCTION PIPE ON TOP OF THE CAR AND IT WAS CLEAR THAT THE LEAK HAD OCCURRED AT THE BASE OF THE VALVE.  IT TOOK 6 COMPLETE TURNS TO TIGHTEN THE VALVE ON THE PIPE.  THEY NOTED THAT THE LIQUID VALVE PLUG WAS CROSS THREADED IN THE VALVE AND IT TOOK A 36 INCH PIPE WRENCH TO REMOVE THE PLUG.  THE PLUG WAS INSTALLED CORRECTLY.  THEY INSPECTED THE MANWAY COVER GASKET AND FOUND IT WAS IN GOOD CONDITION.  THEY NOTED THERE WAS 18 INCHES OF OUTAGE ON THE CAR.   THERE WAS NO CLEANUP NECESSARY BECAUSE THE SPILLED PRODUCT HAD EVAPORATED.  THE CAR WAS THEN RELEASED TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.

THE MSDS SHEETS WERE SENT TO ME ON 12/03/04 AT 1018.  ON 12/03/04 AT APPROXIMATELY 1730 THE CONTAINER WAS OPENED.  IT WAS THEN DETERMINED THAT THE LEAK CAME FROM ONE OF THE DESMODUR W DRUMS.  ON 12/06/04 JIM STALLONE WITH THE FEC CLAIMS DEPARTMENT INSPECTED THE CONTAINER AND STATED THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED DURING TRANSPORT.  HE ALSO STATED THAT THE LOAD HAD BEEN BRACED PROPERLY. TWO DRUMS THAT WERE SLIGHTLY DENTED WERE PLACED BACK IN THE CONTAINER, AND THE LEAKING DRUM WAS LEFT BEHIND EITHER FOR DISPOSAL OR RE-SHIPPING.  THIS LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN OVER PACK DRUM.  DIAMOND TRAILER WAS CONTRACTED TO PROPERLY BRACE AND BLOCK THE CONTAINER.  THE CONTAINER WAS RELEASED ON 12/09/04.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED.  WHILE TRAVELING ON US HIGHWAY 212 IN BROADUS, MT THE LYNDEN TRANSPORT, INC. DRIVER WAS INVOLVED IN A SINGLE-VEHICLE ACCIDENT.  THE LYNDEN TRANSPORT, INC. TRACTOR-TRAILER UNIT LOST CONTROL AND SLID INTO A DITCH.  THE MT STATE POLICE RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT FOUR, FIVE HUNDRED GALLON FLOW BINS WERE DAMAGED.  APPROXIMATELY, FIFTEEN HUNDRED POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED ONTO THE SOIL.  THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO DAMAGE TO THE BINS DUE TO THE ACCIDENT.  THE POWDER RIVER COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND PLACED DOWN SAND TO CONTAIN THE FREE PRODUCT.  HAZ-MATTERS OF BLACK HAWK, SOUTH DAKOTA WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP.  HAZ-MATTERS USED AN INFRARED THERMOMETER TO CONFIRM THE FREE PRODUCT WAS STABLE.  HAZ-MATTERS PLACED THE FREE PRODUCT WITH CONTAMINATED SAND INTO TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS.  HAZ-MATTERS PATCHED THE DAMAGED DRUMS AND PLACED THEM ONTO A NEW TRAILER.  THE TWO, FIFTY-FIVE GALLON RECOVERY DRUMS, FOUR DAMAGED FLOW BINS AND FIVE UNAFFECTED FLOW BINS WERE RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER.  UPON REQUEST BY MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY ADDITIONAL CLEANUP WAS PERFORMED. OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES OF BILLINGS, MT WAS CONTACTED TO PERFORM ADDITIONAL CLEANUP.  OLYMPUS TECHNICIAN SERVICES USED A BOBCAT TO EXCAVATE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  OLYMPUS TECHNICAL SERVICES GENERATED APPROXIMATELY FOUR YARDS OF SELF-HEATING SOLID, INORGANIC, N.O.S. CONTAMINATED SAND AND SOIL WHICH WAS TRANSPORTED TO THE COUNTY YARD PENDING DISPOSAL.  ADDITIONAL EXCAVATION WILL BE PERFORMED UPON RECEIPT OF THE ENCROACHMENT PERMIT ISSUED BY THE MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION.  NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL REGULATORY AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE SAW A DEER STANDING IN THE ROADWAY AS HE CAME AROUND A CORNER.  WHEN THE DEAR DID NOT MOVE, THE DRIVER HIT HIS BRAKES AND SWERVED TO MISS THE DEER, AND THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER LANDING ON THE PASSENGER SIDE.  THE IMPACT OF THE TRAILER LANDING ON ITS SIDE SPLIT THE REAR WELD ON THE OVERTURN RAIL AS WELL THE INTERNAL WELD INSIDE THE OVERTURN RAIL, ALLOWING PRODUCT TO LEAK OUT THE SPLIT WELD AT A RATE OF APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS PER MINUTE.  THE PRODUCT SPREAD APPROXIMATELY 15 FT FROM THE TRAILER AND SEEPED INTO THE GROUND.  THE FARMINGTON POLICE AND FIRE DEPARTMENTS ARRIVED ON SCENE APPROXIMATELY 5 MINUTES AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND SECURED THE SCENE.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT DIKED THE PRODUCT TO PREVENT ANY PRODUCT FROM ENTERING STORM DRAINS ON THE STREET AND EVACUATED 15 NEARBY HOMES.  OUR SPILL CLEANUP CONTRACTORS AND CT DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION ARRIVED 30 TO 45 MINUTES AFTER THE ACCIDENT AND BEGAN RECOVERY OF THE PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TANK.  ALL OF THE REMAINING PRODUCT WAS THEN PUMPED OUT OF THE TRAILER.  BASED ON THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT RECOVERED FROM THE TRAILER, IT IS ESTIMATED THAT 2900 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED.  APPROXIMATELY 8 HOURS AFTER THE ACCIDENT THE TRUCK WAS MOVED AND REMEDIATION OF THE SITE BEGAN.

column168: AT 6:15 A PRELOADER DROPPED A CORROSIVE HAZ MAT ONTO THE DOCK FLOOR.  THIS CAUSED THE LIQUID TO START LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE PKG.  A RESPONDER WEARING PROPER PPE RESPONDED TO THE SPILL AND CLEANED UP THE AFFECTED AREA.  AFTER OPENING UP THE PKG, IT WAS FOUND THAT 2 ONE GALLON BOTTLES WERE PLACED INTO THE BOX UPSIDE DOWN.  THE COMBINATION OF IMPROPER HANDLING AND PACKAGING CAUSED BOTH THE INTERNAL AND EXTERNAL PACKAGE TO FAIL.  THE PRELOADER WHO DROPPED THE PACKAGE RECEIVED A VERBAL WARNING ON THE IMPORTANCE OF HANDLING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CORRECTLY AND STRESSED THAT SAFETY IS NUMBER ONE TO THEMSELVES AND TO THEIR CO-WORKERS.  THE CARTON AND CORROSIVE SUBSTANCE WERE DISPOSED OF FOLLOWING DMP PROCEDURES AND THE NON-CONTAMINATED BOTTLES REPACKAGED & RETURNED TO SHIPPER VIA SALVAGE DRUM.

column168: DRIVER SUFFERED APPARENT HEART ATTACK.  LEFT ROADWAY, CROSSED MEDIAN, CROSSED OPPOSING LANES OF TRAFFIC, AND CROSSED AREA BETWEEN ROADWAY AND EXIT RAMP, THROUGH A GUARDRAIL AND OVER AN EMBANKMENT WHERE UNIT OVERTURNED.  PRODUCT ESCAPED THROUGH THE DOME LID AS IT WAS JOSTLED IN THE OVERTURNING.  THE TANK ITSELF HAD A CRACK IN THE FRONT LEFT SIDE OF TANK CAUSED, WE BELIEVE BY THE IMPACT OF THE OVERTURNING ON UNEVEN TERRAIN.  THE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED TO LOCAL AUTHORITIES THAT IN TURN MOBILIZED A CLEAN-UP CREW AND SECURED THE SCENE AS BEST AS POSSIBLE UNTIL PRODUCT COULD BE REMOVED FROM TANK AND THE EQUIPMENT REMOVED FROM THE SCENE.

DRIVER STOPPED TO CHECK FREIGHT SECUREMENT & FOUND VALVE OF TOTE DRIPPING ON FLOOR OF VEHICLE.  RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  SHIPPER REMOVED TOTE & CLEANED THE VEHICLE FLOOR.  NO RELEASE TO ANY OTHER PROPERTY.

ON 12/27/04, A SMALL LEAK WAS NOTICED FROM A TRAILER PARKED AT AN ONYX ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES TEN-DAY TRANSFER FACILITY IN MENOMONEE FALLS, WI AT APPROXIMATELY 2:30 PM.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT SIX DRUMS CONTAINING A CYANIDE PLATING SOLUTION WERE LEAKING SLIGHTLY OUT OF THE BUNGS ON THE DRUM TOPS.  THE WATER CONTENT OF THE SOLUTION FROZE AND EXPANDED FORCING THE OIL COMPONENT TO LEAK FROM THE BUNGS.  ALL 19 DRUMS IN THE SHIPMENT WERE OVERPACKED INTO 85 GALLON DRUMS.  THE SPILL DEBRIS WAS CLEANED UP AND PLACED INTO ONE OF THE OVERPACKS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE CUSTOMER WAS CONTACTED TO REMIND THEM TO LEAVE SUFFICIENT HEAD SPACE IN THE DRUMS WHEN FILLING THEM TO ALLOW FOR SOME EXPANSION TO OCCUR.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: UNIVAR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING A BULK LOAD OF ETHYL ACETATE TO A CUSTOMER. AS HE WAS EXITING THE EASTBOUND I-26.  OFF RAMP TO I-20 EAST HE APPARENTLY TOOK THE CURVE A LITTLE TOO FAST AND ROLLED HIS TRUCK & TANKER.  THERE WAS AN ABANDONED VEHICLE SITTING ON THE OUTSIDE SHOULDER OF THE OFF RAMP. DRIVER STATES THAT HIS TANKER (NOT TRACTOR) STRUCK IT KNOCKING IT ONTO I-26 EAST WHERE IT WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER TRACTOR/TANKER UNIT.  IT WAS THEN KNOCKED INTO THE CONCRETE BARRIER AND BOUNCED OFF AND WAS STRUCK BY ANOTHER CAR.  APPROX. 706 GALS OF MATERIAL LEAKED FROM THE CLEAN OUT PARTS & AND AN AIRLINE CONNECTION LOCATED ON TOP OF THE TANKER.  THE TANKER WAS RESTING ON ITS SIDE AS SOON AS IT WAS DETERMINED SAFE TO DO SO THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS CLOSED STOPPING THE LEAK EXCEPT FOR DRIPS FROM THE CLEAR OUT PARTS.  THE UNIVAR DRIVER AND THE PASSENGER VEHICLE DRIVER WERE BOTH TAKEN TO THE LEXINGTON MEDICAL CENTER EMERGENCY ROOM AND TREATED FOR MINOR INJURIES AND RELEASED THAT DAY, FRIDAY 12/10/04.  THE HIGHWAY PATROL RESPONDED IMMEDIATELY.  UNIVAR RECEIVED THE CALL AT APPROXIMATELY 6:15 AM.  DOT AND THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER WERE ALSO NOTIFIED.  ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP CREW, J.B. RUSSELL & SON, WERE IMMEDIATELY CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  DOT SAND TRUCKS DUMPED SAND TO CONTAIN THE LEAK.  A VAC TRUCK WAS BROUGHT IN TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL FROM THE OVERTURNED TANKER.  THE OFF RAMP AND TWO LANES OF I-20 EAST WERE CLOSED DURING THE ENTIRE INCIDENT AND CLEANUP.  NU-WAY INDUSTRIAL SERVICES WERE ALSO CALLED AND RESPONDED WITH A LARGER VAC TRUCK TO SPEED UP THE PROCESS.  AFTER THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED, BRUCE'S TOWING WAS CALLED TO UPRIGHT AND MOVE THE TRACTOR AND TANK TRUCK.  WHEN THIS WAS DONE, AN EXCAVATOR AND ROLL OFF BOXES THAT WERE BROUGHT ONSITE BEGAN THE REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL.  SOME MATERIAL THAT HAD MADE IT TO THE DRAIN GOING UNDER I-20 AND INTO A SMALL CREEK WAS ALSO CLEANED UP USING ABSORBENTS AND CONTINUOUS SKIMMING.  DHEC REPRESENTATIVES WHO HAD BEEN AT THE INCIDENT SCENE APPROVED THE CLEANUP AT 3:30 AM SATURDAY MORNING, 12/11/04.  LATER SATURDAY MORNING, NU-WAY INDUSTRIAL AND DHEC WENT BACK TO THE SCENE FOR SOME TOUCH-UP REMEDIAL WORK.  NO WORK WAS DONE ON SUNDAY.  ON MONDAY 12/13/04, BOTH NU-WAY INDUSTRIAL AND DHEC WENT BACK TO THE SCENE AND DHEC, SATISFIED WITH ALL THE CLEANUP, GAVE APPROVAL FOR NU-WAY TO BRING IT BACKFILL DIRT AND RESEED THE AREA.  THIS WAS COMPLETED ON MONDAY.

ON DECEMBER 6, 2004 AT APPROX. 1330 HOURS THERE WAS A SPILL OF MALATHION CLASS 9 UN3082, AT THE PORT/COOPER-T. SMITH CFS STATION AT BARBOURS CUT. PORT-COOPER WAS IN THE PROCESS OF TRANSLOADING IBC'S OF MALATHION BETWEEN CONTAINERS AND 16 HAD BEEN REMOVED FROM CONTAINER NUMBER MAEU7245933 TO BE CONSOLIDATED AND RELOADED INTO ANOTHER CONTAINER.  WHEN THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR ENTERED THE CONTAINER TO REMOVE THE 17TH IBC THE FORKLIFT SKIDDED AND ONE OF THE FORKLIFT BLADES PUNCTURED THE IBC.  BEFORE THE IBC COULD BE REMOVED AND TURNED ON ITS SIDE SO THAT THE PUNCTURE WAS SITUATED ON TOP, APPROX. 200 GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT LEAKED OUT INTO THE CONTAINER AND ONTO THE SURROUNDING PAVEMENT.  THE AREA OF THE SPILL WAS ISOLATED AND DIKED OFF TO PREVENT SPREAD AS MUCH AS POSSIBLE.  PORT OF HOUSTON, FEDERAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES CONTACTED.  AND CLEANUP WAS BEGUN.  THE PRODUCT WHICH REMAINED IN THE DAMAGED IBC WAS TRANSFERRED INTO CLEAN EMPTY DRUMS AND SHIPPED FOR ANALYSIS.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT WAS PICKED UP USING ABSORBENT AND PLACED INTO DRUMS FOR DISPOSAL.  THE AREA AND EQUIPMENT WERE PRESSURE WASHED AND THE WASH WATER WAS LIKEWISE COLLECTED FOR DISPOSAL.  THE IMMEDIATE CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS THE INATTENTION OF THE FORKLIFT OPERATOR IN THAT HE FAILED TO MAINTAIN CONTROL OF HIS MACHINE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: INCIDENT DETAIL DESCRIPTION: 12/30/2004 @ 5:09AM 911 RECEIVED A CALL FROM HES SUPERVISOR THAT A ROLL OVER HAD OCCURRED ON HIGHWAY 154, 1.7 MILES WEST OF MT. LEBANON, BIENVILLE PARISH LOUISIANA, REQUESTING AMBULANCE SERVICE AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE.  HES EMPLOYEE WAS DRIVING UNIT 10583670 CHEMICAL BODY LOAD STAKE BED UNIT TO LOCATION, EMPLOYEE STATED THAT WHEN HE TOPPED THE HILL HE WAS MET BY AN ON COMING PICK UP WITH THEIR HIGH BEAMS ON AND THE PICK UP WAS OVER THE CENTER LINE.  HES DRIVER MOVED UNIT TO RIGHT TO AVOID HEAD ON, PASSENGER SIDE TIRES DROPPED OFF OF THE ROAD.  THEN THE EMPLOYEE PULL UNIT BACK ON ROAD, UNIT PULLED HARD TO LEFT THEN BACK TO RIGHT; UNIT SPUN 180 DEGREES AND ROLLED DOWN A 12 FOOT EMBANKMENT.  THE UNIT STOPPED 35 FEET FROM THE ROADS EDGE.  EMPLOYEE ESCAPED THOUGH THE FRONT WINDOW AND RAN TO THE TOP OF THE HILL AND COLLAPSED.  SECOND HES EMPLOYEE WHO WAS FOLLOWING UNIT, STOPPED AND GAVE AID, CALLED SUPERVISOR WHO CALLED 911, AMBULANCE CARRIED TO HOSPITAL, DOCTORS CHECKED OVER AND HELD FOR OBSERVATION OVERNIGHT.  REPORTED TO LOUISIANA HAZMAT HOTLINE, HIGHWAY 59 ENVIRONMENT CREW ARRIVED ON SITE REMOVED REMAINING CHEMICALS, UP RIGHTED UNIT AND TRANSPORTED UNIT AND CHEMICALS BACK TO FACILITY.  HAZMAT CREW STARTED TO GATHER CONTAMINATED MATERIAL AND SECURED SITE FOR EVENING. 12/31/2004 HAZMAT CREW RETURNED NEXT DAY AND PLACED CONTAMINATED MATERIAL IN ROLL OFFS AND TRANSPORTED TO BOSSIER FACILITY, LANDSCAPED AREA AND SEEDED.  EMPLOYEE WAS RELEASED FROM HOSPITAL TO LIGHT DUTY 12/31/2004.  A TAPROOT INVESTIGATION IS PLANNED FOR THE END OF THIS WEEK, BUT ONE OF THE ACTION ITEMS THAT WE WILL BE REVIEWING WITH ALL OUR DRIVERS THIS MONTH AT THE LOCAL SAFELY MEETINGS WILL BE OUR DRIVING PROCEDURES WHEN A WHEEL DROPS OFF THE PAVEMENT.

DRIVER REPORTS THAT THE HANDLE ON PALLET JACK #16 HAD BROKEN EARLIER IN THE DAY.  A WELD HOLDING THE HANDLE TO THE JACK HAD PARTIALLY FAILED.  HE HAD ROLLED THE PALLET JACK UNDER A PALLET AND SECURED IT.  DURING TRANSIT, THE WELD FAILED COMPLETELY, ALLOWING THE HANDLE TO FALL OFF.  THE JACK ROLLED FREE FROM THE PALLET, THEN STRUCK AND DAMAGED THE DRUM.  THE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AND LOST ITS ENTIRE CONTENTS.  ALL OF THE SPILLAGE HAS SOAKED INTO THE TRAILER'S WOOD FLOOR, OR HAS EVAPORATED.  THE TRAILER IS TO BE DROPPED FOR LOADING.  WHEN THE DRIVER MAKES THE SWITCH HE WILL TRANSFER THE DRUM AND THE PALLET JACK TO THE TRAILER HE HOOKS ON TO.

CST 12/26, ELIMINATING FURTHER PRODUCT VENT.  AFTERWARDS, OPERATING COMPARTMENT DOOR SEALED WITH UP 9509 SEAL.

DUE TO A WET DOCK FLOOR HE WAS UNABLE TO STOP QUICKLY.  A HOOK OF THE DRUM PICK STRUCK AND PUNCTURED THE DRUM.  DOCK PERSONNEL GOT THE DRUM INTO A NON-LEAKING POSITION.  THEY SECURED THE DRUM AGAINST FURTHER ESCAPE OF PRODUCT AND PUT IT IN OS&D TO AWAIT INSTRUCTIONS FROM THE SHIPPER.  NONE OF THE LEAKAGE REACHED THE DOCK FLOOR.

column168: RAILCAR UTLX 46870 WAS FOUND BY AN EMPLOYEE AT WESTWAY TERMINAL IN RIVERDALE LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR.  HULCHER SERVICES WAS CONTRACTED TO INSPECT THE CAR AND FOUND 2 MANWAY SECUREMENT BOLTS LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT, ONE BOLT WAS MISSING A NUT, AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS DAMAGED. APPROXIMATELY 2 QUARTS OF PRODUCT SLOSH LEAKED FROM THE MANWAY ONTO THE RAILCAR.  REPAIRS WERE MADED AND PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE CAR WAS CLEANED BEFORE THE CAR WAS SWITCHED INTO PLANT FOR OFFLOADING.

DURING OUTBOUND TRAIN INSPECTION, THE CARRIER'S MECHANICAL INSPECTOR, DETECTED AN ODOR OF AMMONIA EMINATING FROM THE AREA AROUND TANK CAR CNTX 5012.  AFTER NOTIFYING THE APPROPRIATE OFFICIALS, THE TANK CAR WAS MOVED FROM THE DEPARTURE TRACK TO AN ISOLATED REPAIR TRACK.  AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO INSPECT AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE CAR.  THE CONTRACTOR FOUND THAT THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WAS CLOSED AND SEALED WITH A CUSTODY SEAL.  THE SEAL WAS REMOVED AND THE VALVES INSIDE OF THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING WERE INSPECTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE "SPIT VALVE" ON THE GAUGE ROD OF THE GAUGING DEVICE WAS OPEN AND THE OUTLET PLUG IN THE VALVE WAS LOOSE.  THE "SPIT VALVE" WAS TURNED APPROXIMATELY 1 1/2 TURNS TO FULLY CLOSE AND THE OUTLET PLUG WAS MADE TOOL TIGHT.  THIS EFFECTIVELY STOPPED THE RELEASE OF VAPOR FROM THE VALVE.  THE PACKING NUT ON THE GAUGE ROD WAS FOUND TO BE LESS THAN TOOL TIGHT.  THE PACKING NUT WAS TIGHTENED WITH A WRENCH.  NO OTHER DEFECTS WERE FOUND AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column42: HYDROGEN, PEROXIDE, AQUEOUS SOLUTIONS WITH MORE THAN 40 PERCENT BUT NOT MORE THAN 60 PERCENT HYDROGEN PEROXIDE (STABILIZED AS NECESSARY)
column168: OUR DRIVER WAS UNLOADING INTO THE CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANKS.  THE CUSTOMER HAS TWO STORAGE TANKS LOCATED WITHIN A DIKE INSIDE THEIR BUILDING.  THE TANK LEVELS ARE NOT VISIBLE FROM WHERE OUR DRIVER UNLOADS HIS CARGO TANK. THEREFORE AS OUR DRIVER IS UNLOADING THE CUSTOMER'S SERVICE REPRESENTATIVE (CSR) MONITORS THE TANK LEVELS AND SWITCHES FROM FILLING ONE TANK TO THE OTHER AS OUR DRIVER STAYS AT THE TRAILER.  IT WAS A COLD MORNING AND THE CARGO TANK UNLOADING PUMP WAS BACKFIRING DURING THE UNLOADING.  THE CSR LEFT THE STORAGE TANKS TO SEE WHAT THE PROBLEM WAS WITH THE PUMP JUST AS THE FIRST TANK WAS FINISHED FILLING.  OUR DRIVER WAIVED TO HIM THAT THE PUMP WAS STILL GOING AND HE WENT BACK INSIDE AND FOUND THE TANK HAD STARTED TO OVERFLOW INTO THE DIKE.  THE UNLOADING WAS STOPPED AND THE VALVE TO THE SECOND STORAGE TANK WAS OPEN.  APPROXIMATELY 20 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS SPILLED INTO THE STORAGE TANKS DIKE.  AFTER CHECKING OUT AND SECURING THE SITUATION THE DELIVERY WAS COMPLETED.  THE CSR DILUTED AND HANDLED PROPER DISPOSE OF THE SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE OVERFLOW WAS CAUSED BY THE CSR NOT MAINTAINING VISUAL CONTACT OF THE STORAGE TANK LEVEL DURING FILLING OF THE STORAGE TANKS.  FOR FUTURE DELIVERIES, OUR DRIVER AND THE CSR WILL USE TWO-WAY RADIOS OR CELL PHONES TO COMMUNICATE.  THE CSR WILL NOT HAVE TO LEAVE THE STORAGE TANK AREA TO COMMUNICATE WITH OUR DRIVER.

SMALL RELEASE WAS CONTAINED AND WATERED DOWN & SQUEEZED DRUM SEPARATOR DRAIN.  THE IMPROPER FIT CAUSED THE TOP DOG-LEG CONTACT ON THE LOADHEAD TO TRIP, RESULTING IN A SMALL RELEASE. DRIVER DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF TRAILER AND ONTO SHOULDER OF ROAD. THE AREA WAS ISOLATED  AND A HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM CLEANUP ACTIONS.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY OTHER FREIGHT WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND SHOULDER OF THE ROAD WAS REMOVED WITH ABSORBENTS ALONG WITH ANY IMPACTED GRAVEL/DEBRIS AND PLACED IN A AFOREMENTIONED RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DISPOSITION OF THE RECOVERY DRUM IS PENDING.

column168: ON DECEMBER 14, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR PLCX 221458, LAST CONTAINED CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, TOXIC, N.O.S., 8 (6.1), PG II, UN2922, WAS REPORTED LEAKING FROM THE MANWAY GASKET WHILE BEING SWITCHED AT THE LEESVILLE, LOUISIANA KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAIL YARD.  A SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE RESPONDED TO THE SITE AND FOUND THE MANWAY GASKET OUT OF POSITION.  THE SHIPPER INSTALLED NEW MANWAY GASKET AND PROPERLY SECURED THE MANWAY LID.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES, NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT, AND THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

column168: SHIPMENT ARRIVED ON 10/17/2004 FROM ULA-SANTE FE SRPINGS, CA ON TRAILER 615-9508.  THE FOLLOWING SHIPMENT CONTAINED 12 BOXES OF THE SAME MATERIAL, BUT ONE BOX OF OXIDIZER CONTAINED THE DAMAGED ITEM. column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: VALVE CRACKED IN ACCIDENT, RELEASING VAPOR.  DRIVER ENTERING CURVE - ROLLED OVER ONTO GUARD RAIL ON OPPOSITE SIDE.  POLICE REPORT REQUESTED 12-28-04. (PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE AT TOP LEAKED)  NEWSPAPER IN MOOREFIELD STATED: HEART ATTACK

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: TERMINAL PERSONNEL DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE CEMENT DOCK.  THE AREA WAS ISOLATED AND A HAZMAT TEAM WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM CLEANUP ACTIONS.  THE ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THAT ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A NAIL ON A PALLET WHICH RESULTED IN A SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 15 GALLONS TO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  THE SPILLED PRODUCT ON THE TRAILER FLOOR AND CEMENT DOCK WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  THE SPENT BAKING SODA AND ABSORBENTS USED TO CLEANUP THE SPILL WERE PLACED INTO THE AFOREMENTIONED RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DISPOSITION OF THE RECOVERY DRUM IS PENDING.

DRIVER ARRIVED ON CUSTOMER SITE AND CONNECTED UP FOR DELIVERY INTO CUSTOMER'S STORAGE TANKS.  DRIVER STARTED PUMP AND CHECKED THAT EVERYTHING WAS OPERATING PROPERLY.  UPON HIS RETURN TO THE STORAGE TANKS, HE IMMEDIATELY NOTICED LIQUID AMMONIA LEAKING FROM THE ELECTRICAL BOX FOR THE MERCOID SWITCHES.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF PUMP AND CLOSED ISOLATION VALVES TO PREVENT THE RELEASE OF ANY ADDITIONAL PRODUCT.  DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED CUSTOMER.  CUSTOMER EVACUATED THEIR PERSONNEL FROM AN ADJACENT BUILDING AS A PRECAUTION AND CONTACTED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  OUR DRIVER PURGED AND DISCONNECTED HIS EQUIPMENT AND MOVED AWAY TO ALLOW THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ACCESS TO THE LEAKING EQUIPMENT.  ISOLATION VALVES WERE CLOSED AND THE LEAK STOPPED.  PRODUCT ON THE GROUND WAS ALLOWED TO VAPORIZE OFF. THERE WERE NO OFF-SITE COMPLAINTS OF AMMONIA ODOR, AND NO INJURIES REPORTED.  APPROXIMATELY 39 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WERE ESTIMATED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED.

ON 12-17-04 AT APPROX 9:30 AM PST, PTR DRIVER KEN DUARTE WAS NOTIFIED BY ANOTHER DRIVER THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM HIS TRAILER.  NOTE: VEHICLES WERE TRAVELING IN MODERATE TO HEAVY FOG, DRIVER PULLED INTO S/B I-5 WESTLEY REST AREA AND DISCOVERED THAT AN INSULATOR HAD BROKEN OFF AN ELECTRICAL TRANSFORMER HE WAS CARRYING.  THE DRIVER MOVED TO THE SOUTH END OF THE REST AREA AND CONTACTED THE UNDERSIGNED, HE WAS INSTRUCTED TO CALL 911 AND STANDBY.  PLANS WERE THEN ACTIVATED TO RESPOND, CONTAIN AND CLEAN THE SPILL.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A LARGE 1" COPPER CABLE ATTACHED TO THE INSULATOR AND BOUNCING UP AND DOWN IN TRANSIT CAUSED IT TO BREAK OFF ALLOWING THE PCBS TO LEAK OUT.  FUTURE TRANSPORTING WILL HAVE ALL CABLES REMOVED.  S/B I-5 WESLEY REST AREA WAS SHUT DOWN FOR APPROX 2 1/2 DAYS UNTIL FULL CLEAN UP WAS DONE.  ONE LANE OF I-5 FOR APPROX 5 MILES N/OF WESTLEY WAS SHUT DOWN FOR ONLY HALF A DAY UNTIL DETERMINED CLEAN.

column42: PRINTING INK, FLAMMABLE OR PRINTING INK RELATED MATERIAL (INCLUDING PRINTING INK THINNING OR REDUCING COMPOUND), FLAMMABLE
column168: AT 1100 AM, JAN 30. 2004, WHILE TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED, DRIVER NOTICED LEAKING PAIL OF PRINTING INK.  UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT 5 GALLON PAILS OF PRINTING INK WERE STACKED 3 HIGH.  THE BOTTOM PAIL LID FAILED AT THE SEAMS DUE TO EXCESS WEIGHT.  TOTAL AMOUNT SPILLED ABOUT 1 CUP WAS CONTAINED TO EXTERIOR OF PAIL AND PLASTIC SHRINK WRAP USED TO SECURE FREIGHT.  SHIPPER COULD HAVE PREVENTED THIS BY STACKING 5 GALLON PAILS NO HIGHER THAN 2 UNITS.

column168: A TWO-TON FLAT BED DELIVERY TRUCK WITH SIDE RACKS, WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON INTERSTATE 84 WITH A 330 GALLON POLY TANK STRAPPED ON THE BED.  THE TOTE WHICH CONTAINED ORTHO PHOSPHORIC ACID, BEGAN TO LEAK.  THE DRIVER WAS NOTIFIED BY ANOTHER TRUCK DRIVER VIA CB RADIO AND IMMEDIATELY PULLED OVER TO CONFIRM THE LEAK.  SEEING THAT HE WAS VERY CLOSE TO WATER, HE PULLED FORWARD 400 FEET TO AVOID AN ENVIRONMENTAL PROBLEM.  THE OREGON STATE PATROL WERE THE FIRST AGENCY ON SITE AND THEY, INTURN, INFORMED OTHERS. THE FAILURE OF THE TANK WAS DUE TO THE WEIGHT OF THE PRODUCT, THE AGE OF THE TANK, AND THE THINNESS OF THE SIDEWALL AT THAT PARTICULAR LOCATION. THE TANK DEVELOPED A 2 3/4 INCH CRACK 5 INCHES FROM ONE SIDE AND 3/4 AN INCH FROM THE BOTTOM.  WE HAVE CHECKED OUR OTHER TANKS AND WILL CONTINUE TO MONITOR THE TANKS VISUALLY AS THEY ARE FILLED TO ATTEMPT TO WINNOW OUT POTENTIAL LEAKERS.  ALSO, WE HAVE INITIATED A POLICY OF FILLING THE CONTAINERS ONLY 1/2 FULL WHEN THE LIQUID WEIGHS AS MUCH PER GALLON AS PHOSPHORIC ACID DOES.

WE JUST NEED TO GET WITH THE SHIPPER AND ADVISE THEM WHEN THEY SHIP THEIR PRODUCTS THEY NEED TO MAKE SURE ALL LIDS ARE TIGHTENED PROPERLY SO THESE TYPES OF THINGS DON'T HAPPEN.

WHILE UNLOADING AT HIS FIRST STOP THE DRIVER DISCOVERED LIQUID LEAKING FROM A SINGLE DRUM SHIPMENT.  THE MATERIAL HAD BEGUN TO LEAK OUT OF THE TRAILER AND ONTO THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER DEPLOYED MATERIALS FROM HIS SPILL KIT TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE.  HE MOVED THE TRUCK AWAY FROM THE DOCK TO A REMOTE AREA OF THE CUSTOMER'S PARKING LOT AND NOTIFIED THE CARRIER'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST.  THE SPECIALIST DIRECTED THE DRIVER TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER VIA CHEMTREC.  DURING A CONFERENCE CALL ARRANGED BY CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER'S SPECIALIST GAVE THE DRIVER INSTRUCTIONS TO REPLACE HIS SHOES AND GLOVES.  HE ALSO TOLD THE DRIVER NOT TO RE-ENTER THE TRACTOR OR THE TRAILER.  THE CARRIER'S SPECIALIST RETAINED A SPILL CONTRACTOR TO HANDLE THE INCIDENT.  THE CONTRACTOR WAS INSTRUCTED TO CONTACT THE SHIPPER FOR AN MSDS AND SPECIFIC INSTRUCTIONS ON HANDLING THE MATERIAL.  INITIAL ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER WILL BE PPE LEVEL B.  WHEN THE CONTRACTOR'S CREW ARRIVED THEY MADE ENTRY INTO THE TRAILER AND TURNED THE DRUM UPSIDE DOWN.  THE FOUND A CRACK IN THE CHIME AREA.  THERE IS NO DISTORTION OF THE DRUM OR ANY OTHER DAMAGE.  THE TOOK PHOTOS OF THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM, THEN PATCHED THE CRACK.  THE PUT THE DRUM INTO A SALVAGE DRUM, LEAVING THE LID OF THE SALVAGE DRUM LOOSE SO AS TO RELIEVE ANY PRESSURE BUILD UP.  THEY DECONTAMINATED THE TRAILER FLOOR WITH A MIXTURE OF HOUSEHOLD AMMONIA AND DETERGENT IN WATER.  THEY USED THE SAME MIXTURE ON THE TRACTOR'S FLOOR AND CONTROLS.  THE COMPLETED WORK AND DEPARTED THE SITE.

column168: THE DRIVER FOR CTL WAS EN-ROUTE FROM BUCKMAN LABS IN CADET MO TO BUCKMAN LABS IN MEMPHIS TN WHEN THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED.  THE DRIVER FOR CTL HAD JUST DEPARTED FROM THE BUCKMAN LAB FACILITY IN CADET, MO WHEN THE DRIVER DECIDED TO STOP GET SOMETHING TO EAT AT A CONVENIENCE STORE JUST OUTSIDE OF THE PLANT FACILITY.  THE DRIVER PURCHASED A SANDWICH AND A SODA AND RETURN BACK TO HIS VEHICLE.  THE DRIVER PLACED THE SANDWICH ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRACTOR AND THE UNOPENED SODA IN A CUP HOLDER.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE VEHICLE IN MOTION AND PULLED BACK ONTO HIGHWAY 47 AND TRAVELED APPROXIMATELY 1/4 OF A MILE.  THE DRIVER STATED HE REACHED OVER TO PICK-UP THE SODA OUT OF THE CUP HOLDER AND THE SODA SLOPPED OUT OF THE DRIVER'S HAND AND ONTO THE FLOOR OF THE TRACTOR.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT HE REACHED FOR THE SODA AND BY DOING THIS BRIEFLY TOOK HIS EYES OFF THE ROAD AND THE RIGHT FRONT STEER TIRE DROPPED OFF THE ASPHALT-PAVED SURFACE ONTO A DIRT SHOULDER.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO REGAIN CONTROL OF THE VEHICLE AND STEER IT BACK ONTO THE PAVED PORTION OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE DIRT SHOULDER GAVE WAY AND THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNIT WENT DOWN INTO A DITCH AND OVERTURNED. BUCKMAN LAB SENT A RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY TO RENDER ASSISTANCE.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE REAR WASHOUT CAP WAS LEAKING. ANOTHER TANKER THAT WAS STAGED AT THE BUCKMAN LAB FACILITY WAS BROUGHT TO THE SCENE AND A PORTABLE PUMP WAS USED TO TRANSFER THE PRODUCT INTO THE OTHER TANKER.  ONCE THIS WAS COMPLETED THE UNIT WAS UP-RIGHTED AND THE DAMAGES TANKER WAS TAKEN BACK THE BUCKMAN LAB FACILITY.  ERTS OUT OF BEACHWOOD, OH WAS CONTACTED BY CTL TO MANAGE THE CLEAN UP.   A BACKHOE WAS USED TO DIG THE CONTAMINATED SOIL UP AND IT WAS PUT IN ROLL-OFF CONTAINERS. SITE SOIL SAMPLES WHERE TAKEN AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL IS IN THE PROCESS OF BEING DISPOSED.  THE EMPLOYEE IS CURRENTLY BEING EVALUATED AS TO HIS STATUS AS A DRIVER.  IF THE DRIVER IS RETAINED THE DRIVER WILL NEED TO SUCCESSFULLY COMPLETE A ROLLOVER PREVENTION PROGRAM, ETHIC AND TECHNIQUE DEFENSIVE DRIVER PROGRAM WITH A EVALUATION BY A CERTIFIED DRIVER TRAINER.

THE DRIVER STAGED THE UNIT ON THE CUSTOMERS SCALE FOR LOADING.  THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO PLACE THE LOADING ARM INTO THE DOME OPENING AND START THE LOADING PROCESS.  THE DRIVER FAILED TO PROPERLY SECURE THE LOADING PIPE PRIOR TO STARTING THE FLOW OF PRODUCT CAUSING THE LOADING ARM TO COME UP AND OUT OF THE DOME OPENING.  THE OPERATOR IMMEDIATELY SHUT THE PUMP OFF AS HE WAS MONITOR THE PROCESS THROUGH A CAMERA SYSTEM.  THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TRAILER AND THE SCALE CONTAINMENT AREA.  CTL SENT A CLEAN UP CREW TO THE FACILITY TO CHIP UP THE HARDEN SULFUR.  THE DRIVER WAS RE-TRAINED ON PROPER SECUREMENT PROCEDURES AND PROPER LOADING PROCEDURES.

THE LOUISIANA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (LDEQ) NOW HAS AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE DIVISION AND IS CURRENTLY INSPECTING RAILCARS FOR FUGITIVE EMISSIONS, AS THE EMISSIONS MAY POSSIBLY IMPACT THE AIR QUALITY OF NON-ATTAINMENT AREAS.  THE LDEQ IS FOCUSING ON A CERTAIN INTEREST COMMODITY GROUP.  THE LDES IS MONITORING TANK CAR VALVES AND DEVICES WITH PID (PHOTO IONIZATION DETECTION) AND FID (FLAME IONIZING DETECTION).  ON DECEMBER 21, 2004, AT APPROXIMATELY 13:50 HOURS, RAILWAY CAR ECUX 564072, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINING: ISOBUTYLENE, 2.1, UN1055, WAS REPORTED LEAKING DURING A ROUTINE INSPECTION BY LDEQ (ACCOMPANIED BY LOUISIANA STATE POLICE) AT THE BATON ROUGE, LOUISIANA, KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) RAIL YARD.  THE DETECTION WITH A FIELD INSTRUMENT WAS 120 PARTS PER MILLION (PPM); HOWEVER, THERE WAS NO VISUAL LADING, ODOR, OR BUBBLES DETECTED.  THE CONTRACTED KCSR EMERGENCY RESPONDER ARRIVED ON SITE AND CHECKED ALL CAR CLOSURES.  THE RESPONDER MONITORING THE CAR FOR AN EXTENDED PERIOD OF TIME WITH HIS PID (MULTIRAE).  THERE WAS NO RELEASE DETECTION, BUT HE RESPONDER WAS ABLE TO TURN THE VAPOR PLUG 3/4 TURN.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR DESTINATION.

ON WEDNESDAY DECEMBER 29TH, THE PORT TERMINAL RAILROAD ASSOCIATION NOTIFIED PRAXAIR'S LAPORTE TX PLANT THAT PRAXAIR LIQUID ARGON TANK CAR LTCX #1611, LOADED ON DECEMBER 22ND, WAS LEAKING IN THEIR PASADENA TEXAS RAIL YARD. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE OF THE RAIL CAR, A MECHANIC FROM LAPORTE FOUND THAT LIQUID ARGON WAS LEAKING OUT OF THE BOTTOM OF THE OUTER JACKET ON THE INSULATED DOT 113A-90W RAIL CAR FROM A CRACK APPROXIMATELY 6 FEET LONG ORIGINATING IN THE UNLOADING COMPARTMENT OF THE TANK CAR.  THERE WAS A VAPOR CLOUD BETWEEN THE BOTTOM OF THE RAIL CAR AND THE TRACKS, AND THE GROUND, INCLUDING THE RAILROAD TRACKAGE UNDER THE CAR HAD "FROSTED UP". THE LEAKING CONTINUED FOR MORE THAN 12 HOURS.  TO REDUCE THE EXTENT OF THE LEAK, THREE (3) TRUCKLOADS (APPROXIMATELY 1,350,000 CUBIC FEET) OF PRODUCT WERE TRANS-LOADED FROM THE CAR.  THE REMAINING QUANTITY (APPROXIMATELY 500,000 CUBIC FEET) OF LIQUID ARGON HAD EITHER HAD LEAKED OFF, OR WAS VENTED AS THE PRESSURE IN THE CAR DECLINED TO THE POINT WHERE NO MORE LIQUID ARGON COULD BE TRANS-LOADED INTO THE TRAILERS.  THE LIQUID ARGON THAT LEAKED FROM THE TANK CAR EVAPORATED INTO THE AIR.  (LIQUID ARGON IS A COMPONENT FOUND IN AIR PRIOR TO SEPARATION OF AIR INTO COMPONENTS FOR INDUSTRIAL USE).  THERE IS A CRACK IN THE OUTER TANK SHELL OF THE RAIL TANK CAR FROM THE OPERATING COMPARTMENT ON ONE SIDE OF THE CAR EXTENDING ACROSS THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR INTO THE COMPARTMENT ON THE OTHER SIDE OF CAR.
PAIL APPEARED TO HAVE BEEN PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT BLADE AT THE LOADING TERMINAL AND WAS FOUND AT THE DESTINATION TERMINAL.  THE PAIL WAS OVERPACKED AND SENT BACK TO THE SHIPPER.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT OR ABOUT 9:15 A.M (0915 HOURS) ON DECEMBER 10, 2004 A DRIVER FOR WARREN COUNTY OIL WAS ENROUTE IN A PROPANE BOBTAIL DELIVERY UNIT ON COUNTY LINE ROAD NEAR NORWALK, IOWA.  COUNTY LINE ROAD, WHILE BLACKTOP-PAVED, IS A RELATIVELY NARROW HIGHWAY THAT HAS LITTLE TO NO OFF-PAVEMENT SHOULDERS. THE RIGHT FRONT WHEEL OF THE BOBTAIL DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE PAVEMENT. THE MINIMAL SHOULDER THAT WAS AVAILABLE WAS SOFT.  THE DRIVER WAS UNABLE TO OVERCOME THE COMBINATION OF MOMENTUM AND THE SOFT, NARROW SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE TRUCK WAS IMMEDIATELY DRAWN OFF THE HIGHWAY AND INTO THE ADJACENT ROADWAY DITCH.  THE TRUCK DID NOT ROLL OVER BUT DID SETTLE ONTO ITS SIDE.  THERE IS APPROXIMATELY 10 TO 15 GALLONS OF LIQUID PROPANE THAT REMAINS IN THE PIPING THAT EXTENDS FROM THE BOTTOM, MIDDLE OF THE DELIVERY TANK TO THE PUMP AND DISCHARGE VALVE ASSEMBLY OF THE DELIVERY VEHICLE.  THE JARRING EFFECT OF THE TRUCK AS IT ENTERED THE DITCH AND SETTLED OVER ON ITS SIDE BEFORE COMING TO REST IN THE DITCH ALLOWED THE LIQUID PROPANE TO ESCAPE FROM THE TRANSFER PIPING AND VALVE ASSEMBLY.  THE INTERNAL EMERGENCY VALVE IN THE DELIVERY TANK'S INTERIOR PREVENTED ANY PRODUCT FROM ESCAPING THE DELIVERY TANK.  THE LIQUID PROPANE THAT WAS RELEASED ALMOST IMMEDIATELY CONVERTED TO THE VAPOR FORM AND QUICKLY DISSIPATED INTO THE SURROUNDING ATMOSPHERE.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SHUT OFF HIS TRUCK ENGINE AND ESCAPED FROM THE CABIN OF THE DELIVERY TRUCK.  HE CONTACTED HIS SUPERVISOR TO INFORM HIM OF HIS DILEMMA.  NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCIES IN THE AREA.  THE WARREN COUNTY, IOWA SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT (CASE #44982), WARREN COUNTY EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY, AND THE NORWALK, IOWA FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED INITIALLY TO THE SCENE OF THE ACCIDENT.  UPON ARRIVAL OR WHILE ENROUTE TO THE SCENE, THE NORWALK, IOWA FIRE DEPARTMENT CHIEF REQUESTED ASSISTANCE FROM THE DES MOINES AREA REGIONAL HAZMAT UNIT. BECAUSE THE INCIDENT INVOLVED PROPANE, THE AREA WAS IMMEDIATELY SECURED AND AN UNDETERMINED NUMBER OF INDIVIDUAL'S WITHIN 1/4-MILE RADIUS OF THE ACCIDENT WERE EVACUATED AND MOVED A SAFE DISTANCE FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE. A SMALL SECTION (APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE) OF COUNTY LINE ROAD WAS SEALED OFF BY SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT AND/OR FIRE DEPARTMENT OFFICIALS PREVENTING ENTRY INTO THE ACCIDENT SITE BY UNAUTHORIZED INDIVIDUALS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DELIVERY VEHICLE COULD BE SAFELY EXTRACTED FROM THE ROADWAY DITCH.  A WRECKER SERVICE WAS CONTACTED AND DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE.  THE TRUCK WAS REMOVED FROM THE DITCH IN A PROCESS WHICH CONSUMED APPROXIMATELY 2 - 1/2 TO 3 HOURS.  UPON REMOVAL FROM THE ACCIDENT SITE, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NO DIESEL FUEL HAD ESCAPED FROM THE FUEL TANK OF THE DELIVERY VEHICLE WHILE IT RESTED ON ITS SIDE IN THE DITCH.  HOWEVER, IT APPEARS THAT APPROXIMATELY 1 PINT OF USED MOTOR OIL ESCAPED FROM THE CRANKCASE OF THE TRUCK THROUGH THE OIL FILL SPOUT AND CAP COVERING THE FILL SPOUT.  JOE BELL, GENERAL MANAGER OF WARREN COUNTY OIL, CONTACTED KEITH WEIMER,

UPON ARRIVAL HE FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE, HE REMOVED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN HIS INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION HE FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 1 X 5 OZS AEROSOL CAN OF "ALL NATURAL PAM COOKING SPRAY".  THIS CAN HAD A LOOSE CLOSURE ALLOWING IT TO LEAK 3 OZS OF ITS CONTENTS.  THIS SHIPMENT ARRIVED IN WILMINGTON ON FLYT# 0441, N774AX.  SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS SEALED AND BAGGED IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0338  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

NOTIFIED AT 07:50 ON 12/29/04 OF A LEAKING TANK CAR OF ARGON IN OUR PASADENA YARD TRAINMASTER JACK FORSYTH WAS PLACING TANK CAR LTCX 1611 INTO TRACK 501.  I WENT TO THIS AREA AND FOUND THAT THE TANK CAR WAS LEAKING IN THE CENTER, UNDER THE CAR.  LEAK WAS SUBSTANTIAL PRAXAIR WAS NOTIFIED AS THEY LOADED THE CAR, AS WELL AS OWNED THE CAR.  TERRY PHILLIPS, FROM PRAXAIR ARRIVED AND ASCERTAINED THAT HE COULD NOT STOP THE LEAK.  MARLYN CORBIN AND MIKE MUSTION, FROM PRAXAIR ALSO ARRIVED AND THEY DECIDED TO TRANSFER ALL THE ARGON THAT REMAINED INTO TWO TANK TRUCKS.  THEY ESTIMATE A LOSS OF 8,000 GALS OF PRODUCT.  CAR WILL BE INSPECTED TO DETERMINE EXACT CAUSE OF FAILURE.

column168: RESULTS OF INVESTIGATION: PTI COMPANY DRIVER, STAN IRVING, WAS 15 MILES NORTH OF BISHOP, CA COUNTY OF MONO, ON US-395 AT 1:30 PM ON DECEMBER 7, 2004. HE WAS DRIVING TRUCK #225 WITH A MOUNTED TANK AND PULLING PUP TRAILER #445. DRIVER STATED THAT ROAD CONDITIONS WERE WITH PATCHES OF SNOW. DRIVER WAS DIRECTED BY THE CALIFORNIA HIGHWAY PATROL (CHP) TO PULL OVER IN A CHAIN UP AREA AND APPLY SNOW CHAINS TO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER. THE GRADE SLOPED SLIGHTLY BACKWARDS AND THE DRIVER APPLIED THE PARKING BRAKES, EXITED THE VEHICLE BUT DID NOT USE WHEEL CHOCKS. AS HE WALKED AROUND THE FRONT OF THE VEHICLE TO GET THE CHAINS FROM THE PASSENGER SIDE, THE COMBINATION VEHICLES STARTED TO SLIDE BACKWARDS. THE FRONT AXLE OF THE PUP TRAILER BEGAN TO TURN AND WHEN IT REACHED A 90 DEGREE TURN, IT JACK-KNIFED AND FLIPPED OVER ON THE LEFT SIDE. CHP WAS ON THE SCENE AND THE OFFICER THOUGHT HE SMELLED PROPANE. THE CHP OFFICER ORDERED THE AREA EVACUATED AND CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE. THE DRIVER NOTIFIED OUT HOUSTON DISPATCH OFFICE AND A LOCAL COMPANY REPRESENTATIVE WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSIST. THE TRAILER, WHICH HAS 5,204 GALLONS OF PROPANE , WAS OFF LOADED AND THEN TOWED TO A LOCAL REPAIR SHOP. NO LEAK HAD OCCURRED.

column168: ON DECEMBER 9, 2004 AT APPROXIMATELY 4:00 PM CST, A CANADIAN PACIFIC RAILROAD ("CFR") ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK RELEASED CPX 13 E MG SUPER SAE 20-W-40 OIL ("CPR") TO THE CPR GRAVEL ROADWAY.  THE OIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO CPR BY RANDOLPH TRUCKING DRIVER DICK ULRICH IN A RANDOLPH TRUCKING TANKER. IMMEDIATELY FOLLOWING THE SPILL EVENT CPR WORKERS ARRIVED ON-SITE TO BEGIN PRELIMINARY REMEDIATION MEASURES.  RANDOLPH TRUCKING DISPATCHER SUE NATCHAZEL NOTIFIED THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (INCIDENT NUMBER 743939), ILLINOIS EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT AGENCY (INCIDENT NUMBER H20041728), AND THE COOK COUNTY EMERGENCY CENTER (NO INCIDENT NUMBER GENERATED) OF THIS EVENT. ON SATURDAY DECEMBER 11, 2004, REPRESENTATIVES FOR RANDOLPH TRUCKING MET WITH ENGINEER STUART RUSSELL OF HARD HAT SERVICES, INC. TO SURVEY THE IMPACTED SITE.  MR RUSSELL HAS BEEN HIRED TO OVERSEE THE REMEDIATION MEASURES TAKEN BY THE CPR WORKERS.  NORTH BRANCH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES ("NBES") WAS HIRED BY CANADIAN PACIFIC RAILROAD TO ASSIST WITH THE REMEDIATION.  NBES RECOVERED 1,075 GALLONS OF FREE LIQUIDS, WHICH INCLUDED APPROXIMATELY 475 GALLONS OF OIL.  ON DECEMBER 10 AND 11, 2004, NBES EXCAVATED 60 CUBIC YARDS OF SOIL AND OTHER MATERIAL FROM THE INCIDENT AREA TO A DEPTH OF 6 INCHES.  THE SITE WAS BACKFILLED WITH APPROXIMATELY 60 CUBIC YARDS OF CLEAN GRAVEL.  THE FREE LIQUIDS WERE DISPOSED AT THE KLEENWAY TECHNOLOGY, INC. IN GARY, INDIANA, AND THE SOLIDS WERE DISPOSED AS NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE AT THE WASTE MANAGEMENT, INC. IN BATAVIA, ILLINOIS.  ON DECEMBER 15, 2004, TEN SOIL SAMPLES WERE COLLECTED.  THE SAMPLES WERE SUBMITTED TO PRAIRIE ANALYTICAL SYSTEMS IN SPRINGFIELD, ILLINOIS FOR ANALYSIS ON BENZENE, ETHYLBENZENE, TOLUENE, AND XYLENE.  THE DATA SHOWED THAT THE CONCENTRATIONS OF BENZENE, ETHYLBENZENE, TOLUENE, AND XYLENE WERE ALL BELOW THEIR RESPECTIVE TIER 1 REMEDIATION OBJECTIVES AS PER THE IEPA TIERED APPROACH TO CORRECTIVE ACTION OBJECTIVES.

column168: CHRIS UNZEITIG, MANAGER OF YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR GAMX 6133 SPILLED AN UNKNOWN QUANTITY OF PRODUCT AT THE FIFE YARD IN FIFE, WA.  MR. UNZEITIG ADVISED THAT THE RAILCAR WAS LOCATED AT THE SOUTH END OF THE YARD. RICK SLOANE, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL STATE AND FEDERAL NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  AT 11:31 AM, SLOANE REPORTED THAT THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A MISSING MANWAY COVER SWING BOLT.  MR. SLOANE ALSO ADVISED THE AIR LINE VALVE WAS OPEN AND PLUG NOT IN PLACE.  NINETY PERCENT OF THE RELEASE WAS CONTAINED TO THE RAIL CAR.  MR. SLOANE STATED EIGHT TO TEN OUNCES OF THE MATERIAL WAS SPILLED ON TO THE BALLAST.  MR. SLOANE SECURED CAR WITH THICKER GASKET UNTIL REPAIR COULD BE MADE.  AT 12:15 PM, MR. SLOANE ADVISED, THE SHIPPER, BURLINGTON ENVIRONMENTAL HAD CONTRACTED UTLX MOBILE REPAIR SERVICE TO REPLACE THE MISSING MANWAY SWING BOLT.  12/22/2004, AT 11:30 AM, MR. SLOANE ADVISED THE CAR HAD BEEN REPAIRED BY UTLX AND RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.

column168: AT 20:52, OUR UNIT #107 AND UNIT #805 WERE INVOLVED IN A MOTOR VEHICLE ACCIDENT IN SAN ANTONIO, TX.  OUR DRIVER WAS TURNING LEFT ON A GREEN ARROW AND PROCEEDING WEST ON THE NORTH SERVICE ROAD OF I-10.  A PICK-UP TRUCK STRUCK OUR TRANSPORT TRAILER ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE TRAILER UNDERNEATH THE BELLY OF THE TRAILER.  THERE WAS AN EQUIPMENT FAILURE THAT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION.  THE SAN ANTONIO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SAN ANTONIO POLICE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT.  THE TRANSPORT TRAILER WAS ON FIRE AND WAS RELEASING LIQUID PROPANE FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE TRAILER FROM AN EXPOSED INTERNAL VALVE.  THERE WAS PROPER PROTECTION IN PLACE TO GUARD FROM A SIDE IMPACT ACCIDENT.  AT THIS TIME, THE ACCIDENT IS STILL UNDER INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE.  THE FIRE THAT RESULTED FROM THE BURNED UNCONTROLLED FOR APPROXIMATELY TWO AND ONE-HALF HOURS.  THIS WAS A LIQUID FED FIRE AND THE TRANSPORT DID SWELL FROM THE INTENSE HEAT BUT DID NOT RUPTURE OR BLEVE.  AFTER THE FIRE CONSUMED ALL THE PRODUCT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MOVED INTO THE FIRE LOCATION AND COOLED DOWN THE REMAINING REMANTS OF METAL.  ALL COMBUSTIBLE MATERIALS FROM BOTH VEHICLES WERE ENTIRELY CONSUMED.  DURING THE INCIDENT THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAD MADE THE DECISION TO ALLOW THE FIRE TO BURN ITSELF OUT WITHOUT ANY EXTINGUISHMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EVACUATED A ONE SQUARE MILE AREA AT THE DECISION OF THE HAZMAT PERSONNEL ON SCENE.  AMERIGAS SAFETY TEAM LEAD MARK HOLLOWAY WAS NOTIFIED AT 22:00 HOURS AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE IN SAN ANTONIO.  AN ATTEMPT TO LOCATE THE DRIVER, HAVE THE DRIVER POST-ACCIDENT TESTED, AND SECURE THE SCENE WAS THE OBJECTIVE.  THE DRIVER WAS LOCATED WITHOUT INJURIES AND A LOCAL AMERIGAS REPRESENTATIVE ASSISTED WITH TAKING THE DRIVER TO A NEAR-BY HOSPITAL.  THE HOSPITAL REFUSED TO TEST STATING THAT THE DID NOT HAVE THE MEANS NECESSARY AND THAT NO OTHER LOCAL FACILITY COULD AT THAT LATE HOUR.  THE DECISION WAS MADE TO HAVE THE DRIVER TEST THE NEXT MORNING AT HIS HOME IN SEQUIN, TX.  TEAM LEAD MARK HOLLOWAY SECURED THE EQUIPMENT AND TOOK PICTURES OF THE ACCIDENT SCENE.  THE DRIVER CALLED A NEIGHBOR FOR A RIDE HOME.  THE SCENE WAS CLEARED AND ALL UNITS WERE RELEASED FROM THE SCENE.
THE DRIVER OVERFILLED A 275 GALLON HEATING OIL TANK.  THE #2 HEATING OIL WAS CLEANED AND CONTAINED.  THERE WAS NO RUN OFF INTO ANY STORM DRAINS.

FILE: 2522 F & D, SHIPPER: DORAL GOLF RESORT & SPA, AWB#: TMB 9600136232 LIM  ON 12/18/04 AT 0252 A SHIPMENT WITH AN ODOR WAS REPORTED IN "C" BUILDING (SECONDARY 5) OF OUR MAIN SORT FACILITY LOCATED AT ABX AIR, INC., 145 HUNTER DRIVE, WILMINGTON, OHIO 45177.  PART TIME SPILL TECHNICIANS RICKEY DAVIS JR. AND RONNIE HUFF DONNED PROPER PERSONAL PROTECTIVE EQUIPMENT AND RESPONDED.  UPON ARRIVAL THEY FOUND A FIBERBOARD BOX WITH VISIBLE SIGNS OF LEAKAGE ON THE OUTER PACKAGE.  THEY REMOVED THIS PACKAGE FROM THE AREA AND BEGAN THEIR INVESTIGATION.  UPON THIS INVESTIGATION THEY FOUND THIS PACKAGE TO CONTAIN 2 X 2.7 OZS GLASS BOTTLE OF "PERFUME".  ONE GLASS BOTTLE WAS MARKED "FLAMMABLE."  THE GLASS BOTTLE WAS BROKEN ALLOWING IT TO LEAK 2.7 OZS OF ITS CONTENTS.  THIS PACKAGE ARRIVED IN WILMINGTON ON FLYT#0459, N799AX.  SHIPMENT DID NOT HAVE MARKINGS, LABELS OR A SHIPPER'S DECLARATION FOR DANGEROUS GOODS ATTACHED TO IT OR ACCOMPANYING IT TO INDICATE THAT THE CONTENTS WERE A REGULATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE SPILL TECHNICIANS SEALED AND BAGGED THE SHIPMENT IN TWO PLASTIC BAGS WITH ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND PLACED IT INTO A SALVAGE DRUM.  THERE WAS ONE EMPLOYEE IN CONTACT WITH THE ODOR.  HE WAS ADVISED WHAT THE ODOR WAS AND HE RETURNED TO HIS WORK AREA.  NO MEDICAL ATTENTION WAS NEEDED.  NO FURTHER FOLLOW UP NEEDED.  CLEAR OF SCENE: 0339  THERE ARE PICTURES ON FILE AT THE HAZMAT OFFICE IN WILMINGTON, OHIO.

column168: BRYAN WILKINS, ASSISTANT TRAINMASTER, REPORTED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN THE ALTON AND SOUTHERN YARD, IN EAST SAINT LOUIS, IL.  BRYAN STATED TANKCAR CHVX 288009, WAS LOCATED ON THE EAST END OF TRACK 067, AND WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF ABOUT ONE DROP EVERY FOUR SECONDS.  JOHN MILLER, MANAGER OF ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  AT 08:19 PM, MILLER REQUESTED RMCC NOTIFY CHEMTREC.  VANESSA, CHEMTREC, WAS NOTIFIED. AT 09:26 PM, TIM KELLY, CHEVRON PHILLIPS CHEMICAL COMPANY, WAS CONFERENCED WITH MR. MILLER.  KELLY ADVISED HE WOULD MAKE CONTACT WITH RESCAR TO RESPOND, AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS TO THE RAILCAR.  AT 09:39 PM MILLER ADVISED THE TANKCAR WAS LEAKING AT A RATE OF ABOUT ONE DROP EVERY TEN SECONDS AND A BUCKET HAD BEEN PLACED UNDER THE TANKCAR TO CONTAIN THE LEAK. MR. MILLER STATED IT APPEARED THE RAILCAR SUSTAINED STRUCTURAL INTEGRITY DIFFICULTIES WHICH CAUSED THE LEAK.  MILLER ALSO ADVISED THAT MR. KELLY REPORTED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL PERSONNEL WOULD BE CONTACTED AND RESPOND TO THE LOCATION FOR REMEDIATION AND REPAIRS.  AT 06:37 AM, MILLER REPORTED EAGLE ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONDED AND COULD NOT REPAIR THE TANKCAR.  HE ADVISED THAT CHEVRON WAS IN THE PROCESS OF LOCATING TRUCKS TO TRANSLOAD THE PRODUCT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: WHILE UNLOADING A TRAILER, TWO BAGS OF MATERIAL THAT WERE LOADED ON A LOAD RACK AND NOT PROPERLY BLOCKED FELL AND TORE OPEN, SPILLING SOME OF THE CONTENTS.  THE DRIVER CHECKED TO SEE WHAT THE MATERIAL WAS.  UPON DISCOVERING THAT IT WAS A POISON, HE NOTIFIED ME AND I CALLED OUR SAFETY SUPERVISOR, SCOTT BROWN.  HE CALLED THE REGIONAL SAFETY SUPERVISOR, LONNIE BENNETT, WHO INSTRUCTED US TO CLOSE THE TRAILER DOWN AND CALL CHEMTREX FOR INFORMATION ON THE MATERIAL.  THE FAILURE HERE WAS IN THE LOADING OF THE MATERIAL IN COLUMBUS, OH.  THE MATERIAL SHOULD NOT HAVE BEEN LOADED UP ON A RACK.  IT SHOULD HAVE BEEN LOADED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER WITH PROPER DUNNAGE AROUND IT.
